{ The move that defines the Dragon opening, as our pawn structure is now supposed to resemble a dragon. An important characteristic of this setup is that we have basically no weaknesses @@StartBracket@@the e7-pawn at the base of the chain barely counts@@EndBracket@@, but it does create a target for a kingside attack and White's most principled approach of castling long does ask Black some important questions.  Therefore, I believe the Yugoslav attack lines, in which White castles long, are quite important to know move by move, while slower setups @@StartBracket@@with the short castle@@EndBracket@@ can be played 'by ear'. Though to get that 'ear' tuned right, it is still good to go over all the variations in great detail and study some model games, but when it comes to memorizing a lot of concrete lines, the long castle beats the short castle hands down. }
6. Be2
{ The so-called Classical system. White just wants to complete his development, without any intentions of a kingside attack. It is a decent option that gives White a fine position with a little more space, but Black does get a dream Sicilian, with pressure along the long diagonal and the c-file. We develop our pieces naturally, bring out the knight to c6, and the c8-bishop either gets employed on b7 @@StartBracket@@after a6 and b5@@EndBracket@@ or on the d7/e6-squares. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bg5
{ Another developing move, but it doesn't affect our plans all too much. } 8...
Nc6 9. Nb3 a6
{ Expanding on the queenside. If White responds with  10.a4  , we are happy to have softened up the b3-knight and will proceed with  10...Be6!  . The bishop on e6 puts some pressure on the b3-knight, but also supports the d5-push as well as ideas with Ne5-Nc4. }
10. f4 b5 11. Bf3 b4
{ Asking the knight where it wants to go. Now  12.Nd5  can be met by  12...Nxd5!  13.exd5  Na5  , but going to the side is not attractive either. }
12. Na4 Bd7
{ Black completes the development and the knight on a4 is not looking too comfortable. }
