{ There are a couple of move orders that Dragon players may employ and, while my course covers only the traditional move order, I feel it is a good idea to give you a full overview of the possibilities and explain the pros and cons. }
2... d6
{ Our move order avoids the Maroczy bind and most critical 3rd move sidelines @@StartBracket@@  3.Bb5+  is the most dangerous of them, but I believe it is easier to deal with than the sidelines after  2... Nc6 or  2... g6 and I have it well covered in the sideline course of my Najdorf course, which wasn't published that long ago@@EndBracket@@. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ This is our move order, but I would like to use this chapter, besides showing other orders, to point out how White can try to take us out of our repertoire and how we can remain there with the right move orders. }
6. Be3
{ We can pretty much always go Bg7, O-O and Nc6 against White's systems that involve long castle plans. There is one position we should be aware of. }
6... Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Bc4 Nc6 9. Bb3
{ This is very clever because if we now naively play the same way as we do in the position with Qd2 instead of Bc4 and go  9...Nxd4  10.Bxd4  Be6  , White can make use of the flexibility of not having gone Qd2 and can play  11.Qe2  or  11.Qd3  both of which are better squares than d2 as they control b5.   Instead,  9...Bd7  would be the main move, leading to a major tabia that would have whole new variations for us to work through and digest, just so that we could cover this move order.   Fortunately for us, there is a clever way to get to our lines after all, but the trick is not to take on d4 just yet, but to start with  9...Qa5!  . }
9... Qa5
